segments.text: As I understand it, and I haven't checked out weather records, but as I understand it, about Friday the 9th of July, it started to rain down that country.
And it just rained over that weekend, and by Monday the 12th, they had, they felt they had a situation on their hands.
So evidently on Monday the 12th and Tuesday the 13th, they began calling Jarvis Miller up here to, well, what can we do?
And they set up that meeting then for Wednesday the 14th.
And Dudley Smith called several people to see if we could go down there and meet with this group.
And we went down on Wednesday in the University Plain, left here in the rain and flew down in the rain the whole way.
And when we got down below the clouds at Corpus, you'd look down at the ground and there would be these dark areas that you might mistake for plowed fields.
But as you got lower, you found out that they were this stuff right here, this chocolate brown grain.
And there were just puddles of water all over the place.
So, now as I understand it too, the rain had kind of slacked off on Tuesday, but it started raining again Tuesday night after this meeting, or maybe they were still negotiating over the meeting.
But at any rate, it rained all Tuesday night and apparently all day Wednesday.
And on Wednesday afternoon, the 14th, when we were in session down there, it really came up good.
They had a tornado out west of Robstown.
And there was a field of grain like this that was right across the drive there from the center building that just laid flat between 2 and 3 o'clock that afternoon.
So it was kind of a bad deal.
There were people there from...
The elevators, the grain exchange, the county agents, there were a few farmers and just kind of a general gathering, obviously.
They all were looking for what was going to happen.

And they had samples of grain that had come from elevators and from the grain exchange, and some the county agents had taken and they hid them in bags in there, and they were all labeled by hybrid number and all this kind of stuff.
And you'd see everything from grain, of course these were a lot worse looking when they were wet.
That was one that you might call that 100% sprouted.
And they seemed to pretty well have singled out certain hybrids that were weathering and sprouting worse than others.
And one apparently that they considered to be a bad one from the standpoint of standing the weathering was
use any name, but I'm pretty sure it was a Pioneer 8308B.
And everywhere you'd go, they'd mention this one and have ever since.
But at any rate, they gave us, let's see, there was Lloyd Rooney and...
And Miller, not Fred Miller, another Miller out of Plant Science.
Charles Miller.
You don't have him on this list, do you?
No, he's not really working with the group on it very much.
See, what was it, Dudley mentioned him, Charles Miller in Plant Sciences, when fields dry out, what are the problems?
Right, that's right.
And then the boy from Ag Engineering to talk a little bit about what they might do.
Richard Withers.
Richard Withers.
Is that W-I-T-H-E-R-S?
Yes, yes.
He's apparently new, been on the job four or five months, something like that.
He was simply considering things that they might do from the standpoint of their combine settings and stuff like this.
help the situation some.

Well they gave us about an hour or so to look at these samples and then we went and ate lunch and after lunch we had to get together and make up our minds what we were going to say at a two o'clock press conference they'd called and I bet you there were 150 people there at that darn thing.
All the elevator operators in the area came in there and
And we have this kind of a four or five man symposium, each one of us made a statement with regard to our particular area.
And well, what seemed perfectly obvious that day was that the first thing it's gonna have to do is get it dried up enough where they can get it out of the field.
And we figured that if it had stopped raining right then and
sun had come out bright and pretty the next day and it hadn't rained anymore it would be ten days or two weeks before they could get in the field to do anything.
And that's about the way it turned out actually too.
I didn't feel too badly about the grain if it could be gotten out of the field and if they could clean it pretty well.
And since that time we've picked up bits and pieces from here, there, and yonder
We didn't go down there authorized to do anything or to make any promises to do anything.
We just simply were to go down and offer assessment and hold their hand.
And I told them, I said, well, I can sympathize with you a whole lot, but the first thing that's going to happen is to get it dried up enough to get it out of the field and assuming that can be done.
I'm quite sure that we can feed it because cattle are not extremely sensitive to mold and probably a lot of these things will dry off and probably won't cause much trouble anyway.
But I did say that I thought they should be real cautious about sheep and probably poultry and dairy cattle and perhaps pigs.
This was all a thing that I think was in the back of everybody's mind, but we've had this sort of thing before and of course haven't had very much trouble with it.
Well then O.D.
and I and Neville Clark and Charlie Boyd went down
He was in charge of the large animal clinic in that hospital.
We were down there on Monday and Tuesday, the third, second and third.
And the combines were going, you'd see them going across the field and they looked like they were traveling in a cloud with dust and stuff boiling out of them.
And the grain was being delivered to those elevators and feed stores and whatnot and just had it in great mountains.
What percentage moisture was it, John?
Well, probably everything from 18, 19 percent down.
No, no.
It was dried up by then pretty well.
They could get in there and combine it and get it out and the dust was flying.
Every place they were handling the grain, there was dust and dirt boiling up.
And I know there at Beeville, it just looked like the dust from that elevator just coated that whole part of town.
You know, like a gin in the fall.
You know, that dust blows all over the place.
And the man there said that about all the grain he was getting was number four in sample grade.
And we asked him if he had any market value on it or any market established on it, and he said no.
Really, we're just kind of,
The farmers own the stuff.
I'm just keeping it here for them.
We're waiting for somebody to make an offer.
Well, at any rate, that day we pretty well decided that we'd better try to do something with it.
We still didn't have any authorization from the director's office to do this, unless O.D.
had it, and he never said anything about it.
We went down to consult with Wilk Bank about his nutrition and animal health programs, really.

But it looked like it was such a problem right there at Beeville and we went on down to Perry Foundation at Rockstown and saw some of the grain they had harvested the same variety before and after the wet season.
And they offered to do a cattle feeding test using these two grains.
to get some assessment there.
They had done one test previously coupled to, well, last time we had this problem to a lesser degree, 1972 or 73, I guess.
At any rate, we came back and I called our nutrition group and some other folks together for our brown bag session we have at noon on Wednesday.

Dudley Smith came over for it and at that session in that day we pretty well formulated our ideas with regard to what should be done well in brief what we concluded we'd better do is first of all include this badly weathered grain in our grain quality evaluation

Now we got the other end of this from out in the high plains in April when they were making a strong pitch for some work that would permit some sort of a characterization of grain on a quality basis that would be more closely related to its feeding value.
I think a thing that
caused them some concern up there was the fact that there's growing interest in the use of wet grain, like the early harvested or reconstituted idea.
Does that have to be put in your airtight silos?
Well, it does unless you've got acid treatment, which is the other thing that they're interested in.
In the Glen Deans feed yard up there at Sunray, right east of Dumas a little ways,
had been using the acid treatment on corn for two years.
And he claimed ridiculously low losses.
In other words, something like 7 tenths to 9 tenths of 1%.
And he just got a mountain of it out there just treated and out there in a big old mound.
You know how they do it.
No, I don't really.
Well, they don't make any temp.
Put it in a bin and just pile it out there on the ground.
What does the treatment, though, entail?
Well, the treatment entails spraying what they were using is a product called Chemstore that really is a mixture of about 80% propionic acid and 20% formalin.
And they just simply spray this on.
It's applied according to the moisture content of the grain.
A higher moisture content will get a higher rate of application.
After it's stacked?
This is as it's stacked.
As it's stacked.
In other words, as they bring it in, truck by truck.
It goes through a blast of this stuff?
No, it goes through an auger thing that treats it.
In other words, they spray it on.
I guess you'd call it a blast if you wanted to.
But it's nothing in the world except a little auger that's about a 10-foot auger.
It's got a hopper at the bottom end that they can dump out of a truck into.
It's just a way to pass it through.
The grain goes up this little spiral little auger conveyor, and there's a box that's got metering devices on it.
And it's got some nozzles strung up and down this auger that sprays this acid on there as it goes.
And it's so rigged up that if you run out of acid or if you run out of grain, either one separately, it'll shut the machine down.
So you won't be putting grain in that hasn't been treated, and you won't be running acid through with no grain.
So it's kind of an automatic shutdown arrangement on it.
Well, then this is just simply augured up and they're just pilot.
And we've done some work with this several years back.
The interesting thing about the acid treatment is that it apparently completely sterilizes the grain.
And somebody at a meeting at Oklahoma State here recently, a wet grain conference, said after you treat it with acid, the stuff just lays there like a pile of marbles, even though it's wet.
The microorganisms and whatnot are killed and it doesn't ferment.
It stays pretty much indefinite as long as it isn't disturbed.
So Dean Ray, who was a grain broker at Tulia, met with us up there and he said that he felt that before too long it was pretty likely
all the elevator operators and dryers and everybody up there feel, are afraid that they're just going to get the word some day that said, shut her down, we haven't got the gas for you to operate.
So he said, I think we're going to have to get geared up to handle and trade moist grain.
And that would probably involve acid treated grain.
He said, well, we don't know, we have no basis for trading it.
We don't know whether our
structures will hold it.
In other words, you handle wet grain instead of dry.
What's your load, what's your load different going to be?
What will be the effect of acid in terms of corrosion and wear out of equipment and all that sort of things?
What is in terms of nutrition?
I mean, do the animals eat it just as readily?
No problem at that level.
We have fed cattle at Spur with as much
We've actually incorporated as much as 8% acetic and propionic acid in the total mixture.
In other words, 8% of the total mixture is this acid.
Well, at 8%, we got them to reduce feed intake.
And in other words, they just weren't doing well.
We cut them back to 6% total.
and finished a 150-day feeding period.
So we know that they can tolerate this level of acid.
But you said that old boy was using one-half or one percent?
No, it's about roughly you could say one percent because his grain was pretty dry and he was dealing with corn instead of sorrel.
What's the cost per hundred on that treatment?
The best we can figure out the cost on it is about 17 cents a hundred.
And that is on a big scale.
In other words, if you're gonna do it small scale where they gotta ship the stuff in 55 gallon drums and all this, they figure it's probably about 22 or 23 cents.
Well now how does that compare, John, the economics of drying and storage in say butler bins or elevators or whatever on a hundred basis?
I have a hunch it's probably higher.
In other words, I think that
It doesn't cost that much to dry the stuff.
But you see, you're dealing with a high level of moisture.
And one reason they're using this, two reasons they're using it.
One is that it gets away from the high energy expenditure for steam processing.
And the other is that, presumably at least, the acid has some feeding value.
We know that in ruminants, a big source of their energy comes from these volatile fatty acids that are produced in the rumen.
Most of the energy is released as VFAs in the rumen.
And the two prominent ones are acetic and propionic.
And these two are produced in large quantities in the rumen.
Therefore, it would seem perfectly logical that if we add it to the diet,
why we could manipulate the ratio of these two in the rumen.
So this is one of the reasons we got into it from a standpoint of interest.
It looked like there might be a possibility, and we were able to change the acetic-procyonic acid ratios in the rumen by incorporation of this.
But that's all beside the point as far as this story is concerned.
It just happens to be one end of it.
So they started an end of grain quality and grain characteristics and stuff out there.
And the wet weather gave us the other end down here with a low quality grain that nobody knew what it was worth.
So we felt that, okay, we've got both ends of the story now.
It looks as if we do definitely need to do something on grain quality.
And we felt that since we've got all this damaged grain this year, we should look at it from the standpoint of its physical characterization.
Now, you're doubtlessly familiar with these U.S. grain standards.
You've got a certain percentage of total damage and moisture content and so on.
And you've got one, two, three, four in sample grade.
And the grain that was coming to Beeville was four in sample, mostly.
So it's lower.
Here's what we usually consider a standard, number two grain.
Well, is this mostly now because of, you said some of it was like 18%, and was it also because of so many broken kernels?
Right.
Sprouts, anything, whatever.
But so we felt that, all right, we better start with the U.S. grain standards.
Yeah.

and see, all right, we will do the traditional things that are done in grading grain, and then we better pursue this further and do a bunch of non-traditional things that anybody thinks might be helpful in characterizing this grain better than is being done at the present time.
So that briefly is what we thought about with regard to physical characterization.
Can we do something more than is being done
to characterize this as far as its feeding value is concerned.
Secondly was the microbiological characterization.
In other words, what are the molds and all this sort of stuff going to do?
Have we got aflatoxins, mycotoxins?
And that's where Pettit and Mrs. Tabor come into the picture.
Then we felt the chemical characterization, which would involve the usual chemical analysis plus an amino acid determination
and a gross energy determination.
In other words, when the grain has been through this, what has happened to it?
Have we lost some of the energy content?
Has it been leached out?
In the process of sprouting, have some of the starch been hydrolyzed and utilized to produce a sprout?
Does the sprout pick up in nutrients and provide nutrients to compensate for the loss in the remaining grain or not?
Well, I think quite obviously when you put this through the harvest and cleaning process, all these sprouts disappear, so they are lost pretty well.
So that lowers it by at least that amount.
That's what we need to know.
We need to quantify that sort of thing.
Let me turn this over, John, if you'll mark your place.
